communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chinese blimp incident correspondence
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

* All emails, reports and other correspondence related to the February 2023 sighting of a Chinese blimp near Malstrom Air Force Base
* Any photos or videos taken of the balloon

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

communications.subject: FOIA REQUEST - FINAL RESPONSE
communications.communication:
PLEASE READ THIS EMAIL IN ITS ENTIRY AS IT INCLUDES INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO RETRIEVE YOUR RESPONSIVE DOCUMENTS

Good morning, Mr. Welsh.

I have uploaded our final response to your FOIA request, to the DOD SAFE Website - https://safe.apps.mil

            Please Note:



Upon receipt of the DOD SAFE e-mail, you will have 7 days to retrieve the drop-off; after that the link will expire.



If you are unable to download the documents please inform us AS SOON AS POSSIBLE, so we can work with you to obtain the documents.



If you are unable to retrieve your documents via DOD SAFE, we will utilize the address provided within your initial request and will place a hard copy of your response documents in the outgoing "Certified Mail".  Certified mail is the most secured means to assure you, that your information is being safeguarded. However, please note that if we send our final response via certified mail, it may take up to 30 days to reach you, or longer.



            How to retrieve your documents:



You will receive a separate email from the DOD SAFE website; the email comes from the following email address: NoReplyTo@mail.mil<mailto:NoReplyTo@mail.mil>



Please check your Spam or Junk mail folder if you do not see their email in your e-mail inbox.



The email sent by the DOD SAFE Website will provide you with a website address link so you can access the website.



The email sent by the DOD SAFE Website will provide you with a Claim ID, Recipient Code, and Claim Passcode that you will need to enter to access the website.



The email sent by the DOD SAFE Website will provide you with a Claim ID that you will need to enter to access the website.



You must enter this Claim ID before using our passphrase.



DOD SAFE PROMPTS: (YOU MUST USE THE PROMPTS PROVIDED BY THE DOD SAFE EMAIL TO LOG INTO DOD SAFE):



           Claim ID:

OSI PASSPHRASE:

Semper Fi

Brad A. Beaudine

1. All email correspondence, with attachments, mentioning "Water Property Investors," "Water Property Investor II," or "Water Property Investor III."

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Julia Rock

communications.subject: Fw: [EXTERNAL] New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Records Requestor:


Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen

Dear Mr. Scroggins and Ms. Olsen,

Thanks for the update. Can you provide any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request, or the estimated delivery date? Please feel free to give me a call at 781-962-8816 if it'd be helpful to discuss the scope of the materials we're requesting.

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

[cid:image001.png@01D9C623.0D3F7D80]

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee



[cid:image002.png@01DA121F.C2136CB0]

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Patron Incident Reports - May
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

All Patron Incident Reports submitted for the Area Manager 5 North Region in May 2024.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alexandra Gelzin

Alexandra Gelzin

263 Huntington Ave

Boston, MA 02115

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
June 4, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 164010-67494737@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N015307-051924 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

1. A log of all emails to/from the CPS Title IX Officer, Camie Pratt, from May 1, 2024 - May 15, 2024. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 

2. Calendars for Camie Pratt, from January 1, 2024 - the date this FOIA is processed. 

3. Copies of reports filed via this link ( https://cps.guardianconduct.com/incident-reporting ) from April 1, 2024 - the date this FOIA is processed. RESPONSE : The Chicago Public Schools (CPS) FOIA Office has reviewed your request and determined that, as currently written, it is unduly burdensome beyond the public interest in seeking numerous records maintained in multiple locations and which contain highly sensitive and exempt information that would require a timely and careful review. In order to respond to this request, the CPS FOIA Office would first be required to separately gather the requested calendar exports, gather all requested reports, and conduct an eDiscovery search to produce the requested email log. The FOIA Office has conducted a preliminary e-discovery search with the parameters set forth in this request, which yielded 1,995 search results. Due to the nature of the email search, in seeking two weeks’ worth of the CPS Title IX Officer’s email account without a filter by subject matter or keyword, subject line content will contain, and sender and recipient lines are extremely likely to contain, student information, information reflecting the identity of parents communicating with their child’s school, the identity of employees reporting Title IX matters, the identity of witnesses cooperating with Title IX investigations, details of pending investigations, exempt details of communications between a public body and its attorney, and personal email addresses or other highly personal information, which would require a careful and timely review of not only each of the 1,995 lines of metadata pulled in the log, but the emails themselves and consultation with the Title IX Office in order to determine if any portion of the data is exempt from disclosure. Further, CPS receives hundreds of reports submitted via the link referenced in the request every month, and which are used to “report an allegation of sex/gender-based discrimination, sex/gender-based harassment, sexual harassment (including sexual assault, dating violence, domestic violence, and stalking), sexual misconduct, [] retaliation … incidents of race, color, or national origin discrimination, discrimination based on another protected category, Bias Based Harm, Staff to Student Physical Abuse or Corporal Punishment, Retaliation, or Sports Inequity.” Accordingly, producing five months’ of the CPS Title IX Officer’s calendar exports and seven weeks’ worth of the reports sought in this request, which contain much of the same exempt information detailed above, would require the same timely review and consultation. Accordingly, gathering and reviewing the requested scope of records would require dozens of staff hours to review hundreds of individual records and lines of data, and therefore, as your FOIA request is currently written, the dedication of staff and/or resources is unduly burdensome on the daily operations of the CPS beyond the public interest. This is not a denial of your request. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/3(g), we are asking that you narrow your request, in writing, to more manageable proportions.  If you do not modify or revise your request to more manageable proportions within five (5) business days, your request will be considered denied. If you do seek to narrow this request, you may to specify a particular matter for which you seek records, limit the scope of the records sought, and/or limit the timeframe of the search. To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

communications.subject: Non-Commercial FOIA Request :: N015307-051924
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
July 12, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 164010-67494737@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N015307-051924 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

1. A log of all emails to/from the CPS Title IX Officer, Camie Pratt, from May 1, 2024 - May 15, 2024. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 

2. Calendars for Camie Pratt, from January 1, 2024 - the date this FOIA is processed. 

3. Copies of reports filed via this link ( https://cps.guardianconduct.com/incident-reporting ) from April 1, 2024 - the date this FOIA is processed. As Narrowed on June 6, 2024: Please narrow to the following: 1. Email log from May 1, 2024 to May 3, 2024. 2. Calendar for Camie Pratt from only January 2024. 3. Copies of reports filed via this link ( https://cps.guardianconduct.com/incident-reporting ) from May 1, 2024 to May 3, 2024. RESPONSE : Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Under the rules of FOIA, private information and unique identifiers contained within public records are exempt from public disclosure; those portions have been redacted including birth dates, personal email addresses, personal cell phone numbers, employee identification numbers, and other highly personal information. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Personally identifiable student record information has been redacted in accordance with the Illinois School Student Records Act 105 ILCS 10/1 et seq. and the corresponding Section 7.5(r) FOIA exemption (5 ILCS 140/7.5(r)). Further, portions of records are exempt from release pursuant to Section 7.5(h) of the FOIA, which exempts from disclosure “information the disclosure of which is exempted under the State Officials and Employees Ethics Act, and records of any lawfully created State or local inspector general’s office that would be exempt if created or obtained by an Executive Inspector General’s office.” 5 ILCS 140/7.5(h). Redactions have been made and copies of reports filed at the referenced link have been withheld from disclosure pursuant to Section 7(1)(f) and 7(1)(n) of the FOIA as they have been determined to be factual information inextricably intertwined with an ongoing investigation or disciplinary proceeding. Section 7(1)(f) states “Preliminary drafts, notes, recommendations, memoranda and other records in which opinions are expressed, or policies or actions are formulated, except that a specific record or relevant portion of a record shall not be exempt when the record is publicly cited and identified by the head of the public body. The exemption provided in this paragraph (f) extends to all those records of officers and agencies of the General Assembly that pertain to the preparation of legislative authority.” [5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(f)] Furthermore, this exemption is “intended to protect the communications process and encourage frank and open discussion among agency employees before a decision is made." (Id. at 248, 799 N.E.2d at 864). Section 7(1)(n) of the FOIA exempts from release “Records relating to a public body's adjudication of employee grievances or disciplinary cases; however, this exemption shall not extend to the final outcome of cases in which discipline is imposed.” Further, redactions have been applied in accordance with section 7(1)(m) of the FOIA which exempts from release “[c]ommunications between a public body and an attorney [] representing the public body that would not be subject to discovery in litigation, and materials prepared or compiled by or for a public body in anticipation of a criminal, civil, or administrative proceeding upon the request of an attorney advising the public body.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(m). To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

June 4, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 164010-67494737@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N015306-051924 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

1. A log of all emails to/from the CPS Ethics Officer, from May 1, 2024 - May 15, 2024. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 

2. Calendars for Jennifer Chan, CPS Ethics Officer, from January 1, 2024 - the date this FOIA is processed. 
RESPONSE : The Chicago Public Schools (CPS) FOIA Office has reviewed these portions of your request and determined that, as currently written, they are unduly burdensome beyond the public interest in seeking numerous records maintained in multiple locations and which contain highly sensitive and exempt information that would require a timely and careful review. In order to respond to this request, the CPS FOIA Office would first be required to separately gather the requested calendar exports and conduct an eDiscovery search to produce the requested email log. The FOIA Office has conducted a preliminary e-discovery search with the parameters set forth in this request, which yielded 1,241 search results. Due to the nature of the email search, in seeking two weeks’ worth of the CPS Ethics Officer’s email account (the individual responsible for intaking and responding to ethics inquiries, submitted via email from any CPS official, employee, vendor, parent or member of the community) without a filter by subject matter or keyword, subject line and sender and recipient lines are extremely likely to contain personal email addresses, the identity of employees, parents, vendors, or members of the public witness to or reporting Ethics matters, exempt details of communications between a public body and its attorney, and details of pending investigations, which would require a careful and timely review of not only each of the 1,241 lines of metadata pulled in the log, but the emails themselves and consultation with the Ethics Office in order to determine if any portion of the data is exempt from disclosure. Further, producing five months’ of the CPS Ethics Officer’s calendar exports is likely contain much of the same exempt information detailed above, and would require the same timely review and consultation. Accordingly, gathering and reviewing the requested scope of records would require dozens of staff hours and therefore, as your FOIA request is currently written, the dedication of staff and/or resources is unduly burdensome on the daily operations of the CPS beyond the public interest. This is not a denial of these portions of your request. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/3(g), we are asking that you narrow these portions of your request, in writing, to more manageable proportions.  If you do not modify or revise these portions of your request to more manageable proportions within five (5) business days, your request will be considered denied. If you do seek to narrow this request, you may to specify a particular ethics matter for which you seek records, limit the scope of the records sought, and/or limit the timeframe of the search. 3. Membership list of those on the CPS Ethics Committee as of the date this FOIA is processed. RESPONSE : Documents responsive to this portion of your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

--- Please respond above this line --- 
July 12, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 164010-67494737@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N015306-051924 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records: 

1. A log of all emails to/from the CPS Ethics Officer, from May 1, 2024 - May 15, 2024. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 

2. Calendars for Jennifer Chan, CPS Ethics Officer, from January 1, 2024 - the date this FOIA is processed. 

3. Membership list of those on the CPS Ethics Committee as of the date this FOIA is processed. As Narrowed on June 6, 2024: Please narrow the email log to include dates May 1, 2024 - May 5, 2024. Please narrow the calendar search to January 2024. 
RESPONSE : Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Under the rules of FOIA, private information and unique identifiers contained within public records are exempt from public disclosure; those portions have been redacted including birth dates, personal email addresses, personal cell phone numbers, employee identification numbers, and other highly personal information. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(f) which exempts from release “[p]reliminary drafts, notes, recommendations, memoranda and other records in which opinions are expressed, or policies or actions are formulated, except that a specific record or relevant portion of a record shall not be exempt when the record is publicly cited and identified by the head of the public body. The exemption provided in this paragraph (f) extends to all those records of officers and agencies of the General Assembly that pertain to the preparation of legislative authority.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(f). Furthermore, this exemption is “intended to protect the communications process and encourage frank and open discussion among agency employees before a decision is made." State Journal-Register v. Univ. of Ill. Springfield, 994 N.E.2d 705, 713 (2013). Further, redactions have been applied in accordance with section 7(1)(m) of the FOIA which exempts from release “[c]ommunications between a public body and an attorney [] representing the public body that would not be subject to discovery in litigation, and materials prepared or compiled by or for a public body in anticipation of a criminal, civil, or administrative proceeding upon the request of an attorney advising the public body.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(m). To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

title: Public records request - Business Insider (Auburn University)

communications.subject: Alabama Open Records Law Request: Public records request - Business Insider (Auburn University)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Alabama Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1. A copy of all guidelines, protocols, training materials, educational materials, and screening or diagnostic materials used by the university’s athletics department related to the prevention of disordered eating, identification of student-athletes at risk of developing disordered eating, and establishing a chain of reporting for a student-athlete flagged as at risk for developing or exhibiting symptoms of disordered eating. Relevant keywords to this records search include anorexia nervosa, bulimia nervosa, binge-eating disorder, relative energy deficiency, low energy availability, RED-S, and disordered eating.

If there are any fees for searching or copying these records, please inform me if the cost will exceed $10. However, I would also like to request a waiver of all fees because I am a reporter for a widely read news site, Business Insider, and the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of American universities’ procedures for assisting student-athletes at risk of developing eating disorders. 

In conducting your search, please use the most recent technologies and tools available. 

If any part of our request is determined by your organization to be exempt from disclosure, please release any segregable non-exempt portions. If your organization determines that such segregation is impossible, please indicate why this is technically the case. If my request is denied in whole or part, I ask that you justify all deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the Alabama Open Records Law § 36-12-40 et seq.. I reserve the right to appeal your decision to withhold any information or to deny a waiver of fees. 
Please produce these records in the electronic format and share them with me via email at nparakul@insider.com, if possible. 

Thank you for considering my request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

André Natta, a citizen of Alabama, in coordination with Hannah Beckler.

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: California State Employees (2010 - 2018)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello,

I am requesting monthly copies of all employees who work in the California Department of Corrections and Rehabilitation for each month from January 2010 through December 2018. In particular, I am requesting a single spreadsheet (with different sheets for each month) or a series of spreadsheets for each month with the following variables (where DEPARTMENT NAME == CDCR): 

DEPARTMENT NAME
FACILITY NAME
COUNTY NAME
LAST NAME	
FIRST NAME
INT INDICATOR
CLASSIFICATION TITLE
CLASS TYPE
CEA INDICATOR
TIME BASE
TENURE
SALARY PER
BASE SALARY
ON-LEAVE INDICATOR
UNIQUE IDENTIFIER
SAFETY MEMBER
OASDI
CBID

In addition, please include any lookup tables that may be needed to interpret the data. For example, if departments are listed with codes linked to a separate table, I will be happy to join the records myself, rather than require your staff to do so.

I am comfortable working with large data sets and can receive the records in a variety of formats (.dbf, .csv, .mdb, etc).

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Goehring

communications.subject: PRA Request
communications.communication:
Mr. Goehring,


The State Controller's Office is in receipt of your attached Public Records Act request.  You requested employee data from January 2010 through December 2018.  We are able to provide the requested data from December 2010 through December 2018 at no cost in 4-5 weeks; however, the CBID field will not be on the report until October 2013.

If you need the data for January 2010 through November 2010, it would take 7-9 weeks, at an estimated cost of $1,810-$1,970, depending on the number of programming hours required.

Please let me know how you would like to proceed.

Thanks,


[cid:image001.png@01DAB7FC.22781E70]
Dave Brownfield | Staff Counsel
Office of State Controller Malia M. Cohen
300 Capitol Mall, Suite 1850
Sacramento, CA 95814 | 916-322-7535
[cid:image002.png@01DAB7FC.22781E70]<https://twitter.com/CAController> [cid:image003.png@01DAB7FC.22781E70] <https://www.facebook.com/CAController>  [cid:image004.png@01DAB7FC.22781E70] <https://sco.ca.gov/>


CONFIDENTIALITY NOTICE: This e-mail, including any attachment(s), is intended only for the use of the individual(s) to whom it is addressed and may contain information that is legally privileged and/or confidential.  Unauthorized interception, review, copying, distribution, use or disclosure is strictly prohibited and may violate applicable laws, including the Electronic Communications Privacy Act.  If you are not the intended recipient or have received this communication in error, please contact the sender immediately and destroy all copies of the communication.  Thank you.

Hi Ben,

I uploaded the responsive documents to your request.  There are 8 Excel workbooks, one for each year. The workbook for 2011 also includes a tab for the December 31, 2010, data. Otherwise, all of the other workbooks contain 12 tabs for each month-end.   There is also a field definitions file.   Please not that we have no data for the January 2011.  

Thanks,

Dave Brownfield

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI files: Daniel Ellsberg
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request an electronic copy of all FBI files on Daniel Ellsberg, the military analyst who leaked the Pentagon Papers. He died in June 2023. Here is his obituary: https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/16/us/daniel-ellsberg-dead.html

I request that your agency conduct a full CRS search, as well as a cross reference search, to retrieve records related to this prominent American.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1596212-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for this partial response. In your letter, you write:

"Please be advised that additional records responsive to your subject exist. If this release of previously processed material does not satisfy your request, you must advise us that you want the additional records processed."

I would like to formally advise that yes I would like the additional records processed. Please confirm receipt of my request.

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1596212-000
communications.communication:
The FBI has received your additional correspondence regarding your Freedom of Information/Privacy Act (FOIPA) request and it has been forwarded to the assigned analyst for review and determination.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>. At this time your request remains open and is presently assigned to a Disclosure analyst who is reviewing the records to determine if any redactions are required pursuant to subsections of Title 5, U. S. Code, Section 552 and 552a.


Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: IAPro internal investigations
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request the listing of internal investigations in IA Pro with columns:
 Occurred date    Case/CAD/Incident No    Employee ID/Serial number    First name    Last name    Date hired    Incident type    Allegation    Directive    Finding    Finding date    Action taken    Employee Type 

I request the listing be provided in Excel format so I can easily sort/filter it. Redactions should be done in Excel.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

title: Department of Defense support for unknown entertainment project "The Good Virus"

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Department of Defense support for unknown entertainment project "The Good Virus"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to collaboration between the Department of Defense (DoD) and the production of "The Good Virus," a title which appears on an attached list, released to me through FOIA by DoD, of TV and movie productions supported by DoD in 2023. I request any and all documents pertaining to DoD involvement with the production of "The Good Virus." Such documents may include but should not be limited to: script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of DoD and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "The Good Virus," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: StateStat Brief (Federal Bureau of Investigation)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

- Any slideshows, presenter notes, or handouts produced for speakers at the StateStat meeting held with the JTTF Newark Division at 0915 on 10/12/2023
- Any written meeting minutes or audiovisual records of that meeting

If any part of these documents are exempt from disclosure, please be sure to review and release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of responsive documents. For example, if any of the slides in the slideshow contain law enforcement sensitive data, please black out that data and provide the rest of the slideshow.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Petti

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1613934-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.  Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request
If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-0] please enter [1234567-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1234567-1] please enter [1234567-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000

Case Type:
FOIPA

Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)
The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.
You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.

Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Complex requests are further divided into medium, large, and extra-large sub-tracks based upon request size.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  Currently, simple track cases average approximately 122 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Our complex requests in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,230 days, large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and extra-large processing track are currently averaging 2,370 days for processing.

Respectfully,

Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Department of Defense support for unknown "Religious Freedom Documentary"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to collaboration between the Department of Defense (DoD) and the production of "Religious Freedom Documentary (Untitled)," a title which appears on an attached list, released to me through FOIA by DoD, of TV and movie productions supported by DoD in 2023. I request any and all documents pertaining to DoD involvement with the production of "Religious Freedom Documentary (Untitled)." Such documents may include but should not be limited to: script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of DoD and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "Religious Freedom Documentary (Untitled)," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: City of Seattle Public Records Request Center - Invoice Ready :: C160664-111923
communications.communication:
Dear Rose Terse, 
 
Records in response to your public disclosure request C160664-111923 received on November 19, 2023 are now available. The cost for the records is as follows: 
 
Invoice Number: INV24-C160664-1 
Total: $1.25 
 
To pay online, please follow these steps: 
 Please note that you will need to disable any pop-up blockers to make a payment using the system. 
 
  * Navigate to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * Select 'My Records Request Center'. 
  * Select 'View My Requests'. You may be asked to login. 
  * Find this request: C160664-111923. 
  * Select the 'View Invoices' button. 
 
  * Opens a pop-up window showing your invoice: INV24-C160664-1. 
  * Click on the invoice and then the 'Pay Now' button. 
  * Continue processing your payment. 
  * Select 'Done'. 
  * Once the payment process is done, you are returned to the Public Records Request Center. 
  * After your payment is successful you will receive an email from our payments center. 
Once your payment has been approved, we will send you an email with instructions on how to download your records. Note that City staff must manually upload records. Records will be available one to two business days after payment. 
 
Please let your public disclosure officer (PDO) know if you are unable to pay online; your PDO will work with you on alternative ways to make your payment. 
 
You have 30 days from today's date to pay for your records. If the City does not receive your payment within this time period, your request will be considered abandoned, and you will need to submit a new request. 
 Please add seattle@mycusthelp.net to your E-mail contacts/address book to ensure delivery of the record center E-mails to your Inbox. (mailto:seattle@mycusthelp.net)

title: 1050 Lebanon Road and 1107 Lebanon Road Sawmill Historic Research

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to request metadata relating to emails sent with the following text strings anywhere in the body or subject line, partial or complete:

1 - "1050 Lebanon Rd"
2 - "1050 Lebanon Road" or "1050 Lebanon Rd" or "1050 Lebanon Way"
3 - "ILC"
4 - "Industrial Log" or "Independent Log"
5 - Parcel Number 5611-233-00-003
6 - any discussion regarding Legal Summary Section: 23 Township: 36 Range: 16 TR IN W/2SW/4SW1/4; 9.64AC B226 P164 B406 P35
7 - containing text "Tony Moore" or "Anthony Moore"
8 - containing text "Mary Lancaster"
9 - "1107 Lebanon Road" or "1107 Lebanon Rd" or "1107 Lebanon Way"
10- Parcel Number 5611-224-00-034
11- "drive-in" or "drive in" or "old drive in"
12- containing text "sawmill" or "sawmill on Lebanon" 
13-containing text "LIVELY LOGGING"
14- containing text "Paula Lively" or "Jeff Lively"

Include any correspondence from within City of Cortez where the email address which is inbound or outbound or cc'd: or any other emails.

Please aggregate by the five categories and provide me the following information for all emails sent or cc'd into the City's emails from Jan. 1 2002 to the present to/from/cc/bcc the above-listed accounts to include:

1. From address
2. To address
3. bcc addresses
4. cc addresses
5. Time
6. Date
7. Subject


Please note that I am not requesting the contents of each email. This is lessen the burden as expressed by your city attorney, and to expedite the request. 

I am more than happy to provide documentation or tips for extracting this information from your mail server if needed. Google's Vault tooling should make this request straightforward to complete. E-mail metadata is trivially exportable from the IT infrastructure of any modern e-mail archiving or data retention system - such as Microsoft Outlook 365, Google, Datacove, etc. - and should be deliverable in a .CSV, .XLS, or other machine readable format. PDF is not preferred, and seems to have issues displaying the entire fields.

Please note that I am not requesting the contents of each email. E-mail metadata does not include the contents of the specified e-mails, thus do not need individual review for redaction.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. If possible, I would request a waiver of all fees for searching or copying these records in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public’s understanding.

1. When filing this, please note which documents have already been paid for by another FOIA request, and I request that if those documents have already been screened, that they not be duplicated in cost.
2. Since this is an electronic request, the print version should not be provided, but for purposes of cost estimation, please take into consideration that Cortez population is underprivileged, and extend the courtesy of pricing accordingly.
2a. The economic information for this judgment comes from the submission done by myself of Kauffman Indicators of Entrepreneurship for Montezuma County in comparison to many surrounding counties in Utah, New Mexico, and Colorado. As seen in page 8 of the enclosed and publicly presented documents August 22, 2023, Montezuma County has compensation ranking at 39.27% within the Kaufmann Entrepreneurial Jobs Indicators, meaning that the policy taken by Cortez brings it into direct conflict with the interests of the people they impact should they price these or other electronic documents at a punitive rate.
2b. Because these documents are of the public interest, and the population is demonstrably disadvantaged, the policies of Cortez which require hundreds or thousands of dollars to achieve transparency could be construed poorly in civil proceedings, meaning that legal fees could ensue which would further penalize City of Cortez budgets. This is not my intent, therefore I state it up front that the best course of action would be to ensure that FOIA costs are not borne as specified.
3. Staff time to review these documents should reflect the actual costs, not the maximum costs allowed by CORA law, please recalculate these costs taking into consideration both the public interest as well as eliminating from your cost estimate any documents previously screened by staff.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely, 

Charles Jeter
---------

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Charles Jeter

communications.communication:
City of Hialeah, FL ************************************************************************ Your record request #24-4560 has been submitted successfully. Thank you for contacting the City of Hialeah. We are in receipt of your public records request. You may use the following two links to access the City’s policy on public records: https://www.hialeahfl.gov/DocumentCenter/View/612/Ordinance-2013-85-PDF https://www.hialeahfl.gov/DocumentCenter/View/182/Ordinance-2018-026-PDF These provisions are consistent with Florida law, and we hope you will find them informative as we fulfill your request. Please be advised that processing your public records request may require extensive use of information technology resources, and/or extensive clerical or supervisory assistance. The City has determined that any request that requires more than fifteen minutes to locate, gather, review, redact, copy or make records available for inspection is an extensive request. These services will be charged at the hourly rate of the least paid employee capable of performing the task according to the City’s policy. You may use the following link to access the City’s ordinance, codified at Section 2-871 in the City of Hialeah Code of Ordinances, which describes the costs of duplication and certification of public documents: https://library.municode.com/fl/hialeah/codes/code_of_ordinances?nodeId=PTIICOOR_CH2AD_ARTVFI_DIV2FECH_S2-871DUCEPUDO . The law requires that we respond to your request within a reasonable time. Reasonable time includes the time necessary to search for records, review and redact the records for exempt or confidential material, as well as copy the records or make them available for inspection. At this time, we will forward your request to the appropriate department(s) in the City to determine whether any records within the department are responsive to your request. Once we have had an opportunity to conduct an internal search, we will prepare a cost estimate for time and resources necessary to provide you with your records, if any, as provided by the City’s policy. communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: Public Records Request: GoGuardian
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

CONTRACTS and AGREEMENTS
• All contracts, licenses, MOUs, MOAs, data agreements, letters of intent, State of Work documents, Scope of Work documents, and other agreement documents with CDW LCC for the use of GoGuardian that were active any time between 1/1/2018 and 5/23/2024.

TERMS OF SERVICE
• All terms of service agreement documents with CDW LCC for the use of GoGuardian or with GoGuardian that were active any time between 1/1/2018 and 5/23/2024.

FINANCIAL MATERIALS
• All financial documents or records of financial transactions, exchanges or obligations related to GoGuardian or Liminex. Responsive materials include all invoices, bills, receipts, check stubs, or any other records, including those possessed in an electronic format. Responsive materials include any records related to the funding of GoGuardian or Liminex-related technologies, partnerships, and subscriptions, including those related to civil asset forfeiture funds, grants, and any other funding sources.

MARKETING and PROMOTION MATERIALS
• All promotional, descriptive, and marketing materials in the possession of this agency related to and/or referencing “GoGuardian" or "Liminex" and any of its products and services. This includes all presentations, marketing materials, technical documentation, proposals, or similar records shared with this agency and/or any representative thereof by CDW, GoGuardian, or Liminex and any representative thereof.

GUIDING DOCUMENTATION and POLICIES
• All policies, memorandums of understanding, and other guidance materials generated by this agency and/or entity operating on its behalf regarding the acquisition and use of any data or services provided by CDW, GoGuardian or Liminex and any representative thereof or any subdivision thereof. Responsive materials include, but are not limited to, any data-sharing agreements, terms of use, licensing agreements, data retention policies, and any other guiding materials, such as user manuals, other guidance materials, help documents, or related materials.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

e

title: Police data collection (2017-2022) (City Of West Bend Police Department)

communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: Police data collection (2017-2022) (City Of West Bend Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. the total number of police use of force incidents reported from 2017-2022, separated by year.

2. the total number of police use of force incidents, separated by type of force and year, from 2017-2022 (for example, information that specifies the number of taser incidents in 2022, baton incidents in 2022, taser incidents in 2021, baton incidents in 2021, etc.)

3. the total number of civilian complaints against law enforcement that were reported and the total number sustained from 2017-2022, separated by year.

4. the total number of civilian complaints alleging law enforcement use of excessive force that were reported and the total number sustained from 2017-2022, separated by year.

5. the total number of civilian complaints alleging biased policing or racial profiling that were reported and the total number sustained from 2017-2022, separated by year.

6. the total number of civilian complaints alleging criminal conduct that were reported and the total number sustained from 2017-2022, separated by year.

7. the total number of officer-involved shootings from 2017-2022, both fatal and non-fatal, separated by year.

8. the total number of people who police used force against in 2022, broken down by race/ethnicity.

When available, I would appreciate being sent individualized data in this request in spreadsheet format. If individualized data are unavailable, please send information that includes aggregate statistics for the item instead.

Note that my requests for civilian complaints are specifically for civilian complaints, please do not include complaints filed by one officer/the department against another officer.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Samuel Sinyangwe

communications.subject: Oregon Public Records Law Request: IReady usage time data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Oregon Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

1) For each grade level (or classroom, if not available at grade level), data showing the amount of time students spent on lessons in the IReady system for the year to date. This data can be accessed through the IReady system's lesson time-on-task feature. An example of the lesson time-on-task report from another district can be seen here: https://www.detroitk12.org/cms/lib/MI50000060/Centricity/Domain/5951/IREADY%20Reading%20Time%20of%20Task%20022822.pdf

2) For each grade level (or classroom, if not available at grade level), data showing the amount of time students spent playing learning games in the IReady system for the year to date. This data can be accessed through the IReady system's "Playtime" report. A guide to accessing the Playtime report can be found here (page 15): https://resources.finalsite.net/images/v1701973094/myvolusiaschoolsorg/xjqbs2fxosdtve0tlhi3/iready-educator-guide-learning-games-2-1.pdf 

Please note: I am not requesting data for individual students, but rather aggregate and/or average data at the grade or classroom level.

If you have any questions about this request, including questions about the timeframe or scope of the data, please don't hesitate to ask. I'm happy to set up a time to discuss this request over the phone.

I ask that all fees be waived as I am a journalist and intend to used the requested records to publish articles in the public interest and not for any commercial purpose.

If you choose to impose fees, I request a detailed breakdown of the fees, including the hourly wage of each employee involved and an explanation of the employee hours required to fulfill the request.

If you choose to reject this request or redact portions of responsive documents, I ask that you provide a detailed breakdown of the statutory exemptions and associated case law underlying your decision to withhold each/any portions from public review.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Todd Feathers

communications.subject: Re: Oregon Public Records Law Request: IReady usage time data (PRR 2324-274)
communications.communication:
Hello:


This email acknowledges your public records request of 3/18/2024, which has
been assigned the tracking number PRR 2324-274. We understand you are
seeking the following public records:


1) For each grade level (or classroom, if not available at grade level),
data showing the amount of time students spent on lessons in the IReady
system for the year to date.
- This data can be accessed through the IReady system's lesson time-on-task
feature. An example of the lesson time-on-task report from another district
can be seen here:
https://www.detroitk12.org/cms/lib/MI50000060/Centricity/Domain/5951/IREADY%20Reading%20Time%20of%20Task%20022822.pdf
2) For each grade level (or classroom, if not available at grade level),
data showing the amount of time students spent playing learning games in
the IReady system for the year to date.
- This data can be accessed through the IReady system's "Playtime" report.
A guide to accessing the Playtime report can be found here (page 15):
https://resources.finalsite.net/images/v1701973094/myvolusiaschoolsorg/xjqbs2fxosdtve0tlhi3/iready-educator-guide-learning-games-2-1.pdf


*Please let us know if this does not accurately describe the records you
are looking for.*


*Before we can proceed*, we have some clarifying questions about your
request. Specifically, are you looking for this information for a specific
school or schools, or are you seeking aggregate data for all PPS schools?


Once we receive this clarification, we can proceed with a search for
responsive records.


If it is necessary to charge fees to fulfill this request, we will provide
a written cost estimate detailing the work to be performed and approximate
volume/nature of the records to be provided.


We note that you have requested a fee waiver. We will wait to make a
decision on waiving or reducing fees until after they have been assessed.


We try to respond to all requests within fifteen business days. Please note
some requests are complex or involve such a large volume of records that
additional time may be needed. If that is the case, we will provide our
best estimated date for completion.


If you have any questions or concerns about the public records process, we
encourage you to contact our office. It is always our goal to provide
records in a timely manner without undue delay or expense.






*Thank you kindly,*

Ryan Vandehey

Public Records Officer & Media Relations Representative

Portland Public Schools
Communications Department | Office of the Superintendent

Cell: 971-678-6103

Pronouns: he/him/his

title: Roger E. Guarino child molestion lawsuit

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Roger E. Guarino child molestion lawsuit
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request records related to child sexual abuse lawsuit against Roger E. Guarino (DoB: 9/14/1967), the Sodexo operations manager assigned to MCC until February 2022.

## Specific records

I am seeking the following specific records:
1.) Any communications with Sodexo regarding the lawsuit or Roger Guarino's status at MCC or the MCC Association.
2.) Any communications between MCC, the MCC Association, or  Roger Guarino regarding the lawsuit or any steps taken by MCC or the MCC Association in response to the lawsuit.
3.) Any communications with any other educational institution regarding Roger Guarino, including any communications with the University of Arkansas - Little Rock, where Sodexo reassigned Roger Guarino to another position that involved interacting with children despite being aware of the child molestation lawsuit.

## Applicability of FOIL to the  MCC Association, Inc 

I contend that records maintained MCC Association, Inc, a non-profit associated MCC, are within the scope of the New York Freedom of Information Law. Such records constitute "material received by a corporation providing services for a State university and kept on behalf of the university" (Encore Coll v. Auxiliary Serv NY Court of Appeals (1995) 87 N.Y.2d 410,414) and are thus "a record subject to disclosure under FOIL" (id.).

## Fees

In the event that there are fees in excess of $200, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Edward

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: University of Texas, Austin - April 24, 2024 demonstration
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Any draft (in its native format) of the April 23, 2024 letter to the Palestine Solidarity Committee from the Office of the Dean of Students ("Re: Notice Cancelling Planned Event").

2. Any draft statement by the UT Division of Student Affairs, whether or not made public, drafted on or in preparation for the events of April 24, 2024.

3. Any communications, including text messages, sent or received by the following individuals on April 23 or 24, 2024, which relate to the demonstration on April 24, 2024:
a. Jay Hartzell
b. Sharon L. Wood
c. Nancy Brazzil
d. Emily Reagan
e. Andrea Sheridan

4. Any communications to or from Jay Hartzell, any person employed by the Office of the President, or any person employed by the Office of Governmental Affairs and Initiatives, on the one hand, and any elected official (including Gov. Abbott, Lt. Gov. Patrick, any member of the Texas legislature, or any Member of Congress) or any member of the staff (such as aides, secretaries, or assistants) of an elected official, on the other hand, between April 15, 2024 and April 24, 2024, inclusive.

5. Any communications to or from any person employed by the Office of Governmental Affairs and Initiatives, on the one hand, and any elected official (including Gov. Abbott, Lt. Gov. Patrick, any member of the Texas legislature, or any Member of Congress) or any member of the staff (such as aides, secretaries, or assistants) of an elected official, on the other hand, on or after October 1, 2023, which concerns or mentions "Israel", "Palestine", "anti-semitism", "antisemitism", "anti-semitic", "antisemitic", or "IHRA".

Please also note that this request seeks public records wherever they may be found, including on devices or networks owned or operated by private parties. For example, if an employee uses a personal cell phone or social media account to conduct public business, records created, maintained, or held on the phone or account are public records subject to this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

Section 552.222 of the Texas Public Information Act permits a governmental body to ask a requestor to clarify or narrow a request for information if the request is unclear or if a large amount of information has been requested. The purpose of this letter is to ask that you clarify or narrow your request by providing us with more information about the particular records you seek. The following paragraph highlights the aspect of your request that we find to be unclear or overly broad. 
 
Regarding the second part of your request, please clarify what you mean by “the events of April 24, 2024”. Are you referring to the protests that took place on campus? 

Regarding part 3 of your request, initial searches indicate that the responsive information would be voluminous. The time required to process this amount of information would result in a high cost for you and would likely take months to process. As such, we wish to discuss how the scope of your request might be narrowed to target some smaller set of records. 
First, if there is some specific information that you are looking for that may have been included in emails sent or received by the listed individuals, please describe that particular information so that we can conduct a targeted search for it. The more specific you can be about what you are looking for, the more quickly we can determine whether it exists and release it to you. 

If there is not some specific information that you are looking for, then we ask that you consider providing more detail regarding the subject matter of your request. There are many aspects of the recent protests that these individuals communicated about (examples include student safety, safety of the public, free speech issues, University rules related to protests, student conduct matters, the involvement of people unconnected to UT Austin, etc.). Is there some specific aspect of the protests that you are looking for communications about? You can either provide a description of the subject matter in which you are interested or provide some keywords that we can search for within his emails. 

Regarding parts 4 and 5 of your request, please confirm whether “elected official” includes federal officials in addition to members of Congress. If so, please specify so that we can locate those communications. Any additional detail you can provide about which “elected officials” you intend to be included would be appreciated. Since we do not have a comprehensive list of them, they may be difficult to identify.

--- Please respond above this line --- 

RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST # R006478-042424 
Dear Adam Steinbaugh, 
Following your most recent clarification, we assigned this request to departments and heard back from our Office of Governmental Affairs and Initiatives regarding parts 4 and 5 of your request. Since these parts of your request ask for all communications between their office and with staff members of Texas elected officials and members of Congress, they anticipate that a substantial percentage of their daily communications will be responsive, since most of their work consists of communicating with those staff, regarding a large variety of issues. In particular, since part 4 of your request isn't limited to communications that include certain keywords or are regarding particular subject matters. Would you be willing to (i) limit parts 4 and 5 of your request to seeking communications with Texas elected officials and members of Congress, excluding their staff, and/or (ii) provide some subject matter to which the communications responsive to part 4 of your request should pertain?

communications.subject: Sheriff's Office Records Request :: R001795-062124
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

Our original estimate was based off the fact that a search of our system indicates that we received approximately 1,750 requests in the specified time frame of 01/01/2024 to 06/17/2024, and we believed we would need approximately 1.5 minutes to manually pull each one. Once contacted, the company providing our open records management system indicated that we can run a report that displays basic information on the requests submitted, including: reference number, create date, request status, customer name, and basic description of public record desired. 
According to that company, there . To capture the communications information, the requests will need to be exported one at a time. is no way to run a report that shows all correspondence or communications related to the requests 
Additionally, approximately 163 of these 1,750 requests were filled out manually, in-person at our front desk. These handwritten requests were scanned into the online system. Like the communications information, these handwritten requests will need to be exported one at a time. 
You can reduce the estimated time and cost to complete your request by withdrawing the portion of your request that was asking for communications related to each request, thereby reducing the need to export each request one at a time. Keep in mind, even if you withdraw the communications portion of your request, the handwritten requests described above will still need to be exported one at a time. The cost estimate for that is option is listed below. 
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
163 requests x 1.5 min processing time = 244.5 min (4.08 hours) 
LABOR 
4.08 hours x $15/hr = $61.13 
OVERHEAD 
$61.13 x 20% = $12.23 
TOTAL 
$61.13 + $12.23 = $ 73.36 
Sincerely, 
Lisa Foster
